<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1887-11-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1887-11-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="543" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d543">
                        <head>No. 543.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">L. S.
                                    Sackville West</persName>to Mr. <persName type="to">Bayard</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1887-11-29"><hi rend="italic">November</hi> 29,
                                    1887</date>. (Received November 30.)</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to your note of the 12th
                            instant I have the honor to inform you that the Marquis of Salisbury has
                            requested me to ask you whether any member of the staff of the United
                            States legation in London could properly attend the sugar
                            conference.</p>
                        <p>I may add that the chargés d’affaires of France and Italy will attend,
                            and that the conference will not conclude its labors for some time to
                            come.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc,</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">L. S. Sackville
                                    West</hi></persName>.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>